# managed-services.allow — operator-owned allowlist of the LOCAL services THIS node
# is allowed to control (systemctl / service / pm2 / docker / podman).
#
# Install as ~/.claude/managed-services.allow (or point CCC_MANAGED_SERVICES_ALLOW at
# it). One unit/container/process name per line. `#` starts a comment; blank lines are
# ignored. fnmatch globs are supported (`*`, `?`, `[...]`). A trailing `.service` is
# tolerated — an entry `myapp` matches both `myapp` and `myapp.service`.
#
# What it does: fleet services (a2a/hermes/openclaw/broker/gateway/worker,
# ccc-telegram-bridge) are already autonomous. This file lets the node ALSO manage its
# OWN non-fleet local apps by name — `systemctl restart myapp`, `pm2 restart myapp`,
# `docker restart my-container` — when every target of the command is listed here.
#
# What it does NOT do (stays fail-closed):
#   - a command whose targets are not ALL listed (e.g. `systemctl restart myapp sshd`)
#     is denied — you cannot slip an unlisted unit in alongside a listed one;
#   - system services you did not list (sshd, ufw, nginx, postgresql, …) stay gated;
#   - targetless/global forms (`systemctl daemon-reload`), Compose lifecycle other
#     than a direct local detached `docker compose up -d`, a docker remote-daemon
#     flag (`docker -H …`), and command-substitution targets are gated;
#   - kubectl is never relaxed here.
#
# TRUST: this file is the boundary that says "these local services are mine to
# control." guard.py denies agent writes to it (Edit/Write and shell redirect/
# interpreter writes) — only YOU edit it. Do NOT list a shared system service
# (sshd/ufw/networking/…) whose restart could lock you out or disable security.

# --- examples (delete these; add your real local apps) ---
# myapp
# mydashboard
# my-container
# web-*
